claims:
1. An ignition apparatus comprising:
      (a) an excitation light source; 
      (b) a light modulator positioned to receive output from said excitation light source; 
      (c) a first polarization analyzer positioned to receive light from said light modulator; 
      (d) a first output coupler positioned to receive a portion of light not redirected by said first polarization analyzer; 
      (e) a focusing lens positioned to inject said portion of light not redirected by said first polarization analyzer from said first output coupler into a first end of a first optical fiber; 
      (f) a second end of said first optical fiber connected to an ignitor laser so as to permit transport of said portion of light not redirected by said first polarization analyzer into a first lasing rod in said ignitor laser; 
      (g) a second output coupler positioned to receive a portion of light redirected by said first polarization analyzer; 
      (h) a halfwave plate positioned to receive from said second output coupler said portion of light redirected by said first polarization analyzer; 
      (i) a second polarization analyzer positioned to receive output from said halfwave plate; 
      (j) a second focusing lens positioned to inject light redirected by said second polarization analyzer into a first end of a second optical fiber; 
      (k) a second end of said second optical fiber connected to said ignitor laser so as to permit transport of said portion of light redirected by said first polarization analyzer into a beam combiner in said ignitor laser; 
      (l) a third focusing lens positioned to inject a portion of light not redirected by said second polarization analyzer into a first end of a third optical fiber; 
      (m) a second end of said third optical fiber connected to said ignitor laser so as to permit transport of said portion of light not redirected by said second polarization analyzer into a second lasing rod in said ignitor laser; 
      (n) an output coupler positioned to receive output from said second lasing rod in said ignitor laser; 
      (o) at least one turning prism to direct said output from said second lasing rod in said ignitor laser into said first lasing rod in said ignitor laser; 
      (p) said beam combiner also positioned to receive output from said first lasing rod in said ignitor laser; and 
      (q) an ignitor output focusing lens positioned to direct output from said beam combiner into a combustible fuel.

14. An ignition method comprising:
      (a) directing a beam from an excitation light source into a laser light modulator; 
      (b) applying a voltage to said laser light modulator intermittently in accordance with signals from a timing module, thereby controlling polarization of said laser light; 
      (c) directing said laser light from said laser light modulator into a first polarization analyzer which either rejects or transports said laser light according to whether or not said laser light has been polarized by said laser light modulator; 
      (d) directing any said laser light which is transported by said first polarization analyzer through a first focusing lens into a first optical fiber, and thence into a first laser rod in an ignitor laser; 
      (e) splitting beam of any said laser light rejected by said first polarization analyzer into a first portion and a second portion; 
      (f) directing said first portion of said laser light rejected by said first polarization analyzer through a second focusing lens into a second optical fiber and thence into a beam combiner; 
      (g) directing said second portion of said laser light rejected by said first polarization analyzer through a third focusing lens into a third optical fiber, and thence into a second laser rod in said ignitor laser; 
      (h) directing output of said second laser rod in said ignitor laser into said first leaser rod in said ignitor laser; 
      (i) combining output of said first laser rod in said ignitor laser in said beam combiner with any light rejected by said second polarization analyzer to form a combined beam; 
      (j) directing said combined beam through a focusing lens into a combustible fuel.
